[SN]TITLE[SN]
FTSE 100 rebounds as Sainsbury's lifts profit outlook

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
(Close): UK shares enjoyed strong gains on Wednesday, helped by Sainsbury's after the supermarket group lifted its full-year profit outlook.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
Despite reporting a seventh straight quarter of falling sales, it said profits were set to beat forecasts.
Sainsbury's shares soared 13.8%, and the FTSE 100 index rose 152.37 points, or 2.6%, to 6,061.61.
Other supermarkets were also lifted by Sainsbury's news, with Morrisons up 6.4% and Tesco 6.9% higher.
Shares in mining giant Glencore continued to recover from Monday's 30% fall. Its shares were the best performer, up 14%, having risen 17% on Tuesday after it issued a statement saying it was "financially robust".
In the FTSE 250, shares in Entertainment One fell 8.8% after the company said it would use a rights issue to fund the purchase of a 70% stake in Astley Baker Davies (ABD), the creator and producer of Peppa Pig. Entertainment One already jointly owns the rights to Peppa Pig with APD.
